<font color="#FF0000">TANKS IN NAM?</font><br>
<tt>Wed Sep 17 13:20:21 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Gosh, Darn, <br>
Tanks. <br>
Tanks were useless in Nam {G}. Everywhere they went we had to provide security for them. What good are tanks when grunts had to baby-sit them? <br>
We were on Saint Peter, a flat hill with no shade searching for rocket sites Charlie was using to pop into DaNang with the North's latest supply of 122mm rocketst they had acquired straight from Communist block countries. <br>
Our position we knew could easily be overrun, so we asked for a tank. Figured we could at least use it string up our hammocks. All we wanted was just a simple Army tank. We just wanted it for the noise it made, we all knew tankers can't shoot straight but Charlie still didn't know it. The whole 1st armored division was in the area. No one wanted to come. One platoon of Marines wasn't enough to protect the tank crew we were told. <br>
There was no road for them to travel on,<br>
They didn't have a tow vehicle available if the tank got stuck, <br>
Their tracks might get mud on them and<br>
The new 1st cal Armoured Division decals weren't dry, yet. Above everything else they wanted to know if there were any NVA in the area that might have RPG rockets with them. <br>
So, Dumont, we called him Frenchy, cause he could speak French, we figured that out ourselves. Dumont stole a six-by changed its timing and at night we just rapped it up. Gooks must have though we had tanks with us and stayed away.  Never needed tin cans after that. True Story, just changed a little bit. <br>
Oh! Captain Robb used a tank once. Real impressive, the press took a lot of nice pictures.<br>
I was so proud of my captain standing there on top of that newly polished tank. <br>
There Captain Charles S. Robb, stood with his withdrawn .45 cal pistol standing on top of this glorified budweiser can painted green in Dodge City, (actually, we couldn't go beyond a little creek crossing on account the tanks might get stuck and the ROCK Marines on the other side didn't want Robb, and the press messing with the hunt they were conducting in the area). But, it made a nice picture. I think that was the only time we used tanks in Nam.<br><br>
Traded a lot of captured gook stuff with tankers. Felt sorry for them and wanted to give them something to write home about. Knew they were frustrated, cause after all that book learning on how to fire their Mechanized mortar tubes they were allowed off the hill. It wasn't their fault.
<p><code>-- Sparrowhawk  (Cook Barela) </code><p>


